        ## Pollution detection

        After viability assays showing that  *E. coli* can survive with the chosen pollutants present, the inducibility of the promoters was checked. In tests with similar pollution levels found in the environment and the high levels neither induced the promoters. 

        # *S. oneidensis* oscillation

        ## *E. coli* successful gene insertion

        Shewanella oneidensis requires conjugation or electroporation for optimal gene insertions. The following gene insertions were performed with E. coli as a representative organism. Firstly, the oscillation gene circuit insertion in *E. coli* was evaluated by Sanger sequencing. The parts, [BBa_K3440014](http://parts.igem.org/Part:BBa_K3440014) (Constitutive promoter- LuxR- myc tag-Inducible Promoter Lux-GFP) and [BBa_K3440012](http://parts.igem.org/Part:BBa_K3440012) (Constitutive promoter- RhlR- myc tag- inducible Promoter Rhl-GFP) respectively, were successfully inserted in *E. coli* and characterized. These parts are required for the oscillation to occur, with the exception of the GFP and myc-tag which was used to evaluate protein expression. The protein expression of LuxI, LuxR and RhlI; LuxR and RhlR could be induced by AHL and/or constructs expressing LuxI and RhlI. 
        With these results as and the successful expression of LuxI and RhlI in co-cultures and with no synthetic AHL suggests successful binding to LuxR and RhlR respectively and induction of specific promoters and expression of GFP. The results of this functionality assay are supported by the [Western blot results](https://2020.igem.org/Team:Stockholm/Results#WesternBlot), which showed the expression of Myc-tagged Lux, RhlI  and LuxR.

